{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17648087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17648087"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:49:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:49:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18274"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18274"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0,0.85,0.11,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10988"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74023"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10988","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10988"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18274"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59499"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4899"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7418"},{"type":"tags","id":"7437"},{"type":"tags","id":"7440"},{"type":"tags","id":"11443"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25525"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25528"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74023"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following ligaments is the medial meniscus tethered to, contributing to its relative immobility?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Posterior cruciate ligament","Lateral collateral ligament","Medial collateral ligament","Anterior cruciate ligament","Fibular collateral ligament"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe medial meniscus is a C-shaped cartilage structure in the knee joint. It plays a crucial role in shock absorption and stability of the knee.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe medial meniscus is tethered to the \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial collateral ligament\u003C/strong\u003E, which contributes to its relative immobility. This attachment makes the medial meniscus more susceptible to injury compared to the lateral meniscus, which is not attached to the lateral collateral ligament.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior cruciate ligament\u003C/strong\u003E - This ligament is located within the knee joint and does not attach to the menisci\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral collateral ligament\u003C/strong\u003E - This ligament is on the lateral side of the knee and does not attach to the menisci\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior cruciate ligament\u003C/strong\u003E - This ligament is located within the knee joint and does not attach to the menisci\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibular collateral ligament\u003C/strong\u003E - This is another name for the lateral collateral ligament and does not attach to the menisci\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The medial meniscus is C-shaped and is more prone to injury due to its relative immobility.","The medial meniscus is tethered to the medial collateral ligament, which restricts its movement.","The lateral meniscus is more mobile compared to the medial meniscus because it is not attached to the lateral collateral ligament."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629","Chaudhry SR, Nahian A, Chaudhry K. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis, Pelvis. [Updated 2023 Jul 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482258/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59499"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18274"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59499"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T09:06:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T09:07:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10988"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74023"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links